element_texts.text:
The 15th of the 2th month called Aprill Ann. Do: 1639
Wee Webb Cowett, & Squaw Sachem do sell vnto the inhabitants
of the towne of Charles towne all the land within their lines gran-
ted them by the Court (excepting the farmes) and Ground on the west
side of the two great ponds called mistick ponds from the 
south side of Mr. Nowells lott neare the vpper end of the
ponds vnto the little runnet which cometh from Captaine Cookes
Mill, which the squaw reserveth for theire vse for her life for 
the Indians to plant, & hunt vppon, and the weire above the ponds
they also reserve for the Indians to fish at whilst the Squaw liveth
and after the death of Squaw Sachem shee doth leave all her
lands from Mr Mayhew house to neare Salem to the present
Governour Mr John Winthrope senior, Mr Increase Nowell, Mr In[superscript o]
Wilson, and Mr Edw. Gibons to dispose of, and all Indians to depart
and for satisfaction from Charles=towne, wee acknowledge to have 
received in full satisfaction twenty and one coates 19 fathome
of Wampam, and three bushells of Corne: in witness whereof, 
wee have herevnto set our hands the day, and yeare above-
named.
subscribed in the presence  of us
Robert Feke
John Humphey
Memorandum that these wordes 
all the land were interlined before the subscription.
The mark of [jagged line] Squaw Sachem.
The mark [wavy line] of Web Cowett.
This is to testify that the aforenamed purchase was made at the charges
of the Inhabitants of Charles towne, and to theire vse, and for so
much as lyeth within in theire limitts, wee doe accordingly resigne,
and yeild vp all our interest therein, to the vse of the said towne,
according to the trust reposed in us. 10th. mo. 18th 1639.
In[superscript o] Winthrop Govern[ou]r
Increase Nowell
In[superscript o] Wilson
Entred & Recorded 23th (8) Mo. 1656
By Thomas Danforth. Record[e]r
